ğŸ”„ Range-Based For Loop in C++
ğŸ“Œ What is a Range-Based For Loop?
A range-based for loop provides a clean and readable way to iterate over elements of containers like vectors, sets, arrays, etc.

It was introduced in C++11.

ğŸ§  Syntax:
cpp
Copy
Edit
for (auto variable : container) {
    // logic
}
âœ… Example (Graph Edge Iteration):
cpp
Copy
Edit
vector<vector<int>> edges = {{1, 2}, {2, 3}, {2, 4}};
unordered_map<int, int> degree;

for (auto edge : edges) {
    degree[edge[0]]++;
    degree[edge[1]]++;
}
ğŸ” Equivalent Traditional For Loop:
cpp
Copy
Edit
for (int i = 0; i < edges.size(); i++) {
    vector<int> edge = edges[i];
    degree[edge[0]]++;
    degree[edge[1]]++;
}
ğŸ’¡ Why Use It?
Advantage	Description
âœ… Cleaner Syntax	No need to manage indices manually
âœ… Reduces Bugs	Avoids off-by-one and index errors
âœ… Works with Any Container	STL vector, set, map, arrays, etc.
âœ… Better Readability	Code looks more like pseudocode

âš ï¸ Things to Note:
If you want to modify the elements, use reference:

cpp
Copy
Edit
for (auto& edge : edges) {
    // modify edge directly
}
If you're only reading, auto by value is fine.

ğŸ“‚ Use Case in Competitive Programming / Graphs:
Used commonly in:

Traversing edge lists.

BFS/DFS traversal.

Processing adjacency lists/maps.

ğŸ Final Tip:
Prefer range-based loops when readability is more important than manual index control. It makes the logic concise and easier to debug.

